    <subfield code="m">SUPPLEMENTARY MATERIAL Stability analysis of the spiral ground state In this section we supply some of the technical details pertaining to the stability analysis of the spiral ground state. In this analysis it is useful to consider a spinonly effective theory that arises upon integrating out the electron degrees of freedom in the relevant Hamiltonian given e.g. by Eq. (1) in the main text. More generally, we start from a Hamiltonian of the form H = H0 + J i Si · (c† iσσσσ ciσ ) (14) where H0 describes the electrons in the absence of the exchange coupling to the magnetic moments Si. Assuming translational invariance we can integrate out the electrons to obtain the effective spin-only Hamiltonian HS = J2 2 q χαβ (q)Sα q Sβ</subfield>
